  "prompt": "What are the causes of having itchy small blisters on my fingers?",
  "response": "Itchy small blisters on your fingers can be caused by several conditions. Here are some common causes:\n\n### 1. **Dyshidrotic Eczema (Pompholyx)**\n   - **Description:** A type of eczema that causes small, intensely itchy blisters on the hands and fingers.\n   - **Triggers:** Stress, allergies, exposure to irritants (like detergents or metals), and sweating.\n   - **Symptoms:** Clear, fluid-filled blisters, redness, and scaling.\n\n### 2. **Contact Dermatitis**\n   - **Description:** An allergic or irritant reaction to substances your fingers come into contact with.\n   - **Triggers:** Soaps, cleaning products, latex, metals (like nickel), or plants (e.g., poison ivy).\n   - **Symptoms:** Itchy, red, or blistered skin in areas exposed to the irritant.\n\n### 3. **Fungal Infections (e.g., Tinea Manuum)**\n   - **Description:** A fungal infection affecting the hands, often caused by the same fungi that cause athlete's foot.\n   - **Triggers:** Contact with infected surfaces or skin-to-skin contact.\n   - **Symptoms:** Itching, scaling, and sometimes blisters.\n\n### 4. **Scabies**\n   - **Description:** A contagious skin infestation caused by microscopic mites.\n   - **Triggers:** Close contact with an infected person or contaminated objects.\n   - **Symptoms:** Intense itching, especially at night, and small blisters or burrows in the skin.\n\n### 5. **Herpetic Whitlow**\n   - **Description:** A viral infection caused by the herpes simplex virus (HSV) affecting the fingers.\n   - **Triggers:** Direct contact with an HSV-infected area.\n   - **Symptoms:** Painful, fluid-filled blisters, redness, and swelling.\n\n### 6. **Insect Bites**\n   - **Description:** Allergic reactions to bites from insects like mosquitoes or spiders.\n   - **Triggers:** Exposure to insects.\n   - **Symptoms:** Itchy, red bumps or blisters at the site of the bite.\n\n### 7. **Allergic Reaction**\n   - **Description:** An immune response to allergens like food, medication, or environmental factors.\n   - **Triggers:** Exposure to specific allergens.\n   - **Symptoms:** Itching, hives, or blisters.\n\n### 8. **Heat Rash (Miliaria)**\n   - **Description:** A skin condition caused by blocked sweat ducts.\n   - **Triggers:** Hot and humid weather or excessive sweating.\n   - **Symptoms:** Tiny, itchy blisters or red bumps.\n\n### 9. **Autoimmune Conditions (e.g., Pemphigus Vulgaris)**\n   - **Description:** Rare autoimmune disorders that cause blistering of the skin.\n   - **Triggers:** Unknown, but immune system dysfunction plays a role.\n   - **Symptoms:** Painful blisters and sores.\n\n### When to See a Doctor:\n- If the blisters persist, worsen, or are accompanied by fever, pain, or signs of infection (e.g., pus or spreading redness).\n- If you suspect a contagious condition like scabies or herpetic whitlow.\n\n### Prevention and Management:\n- Avoid irritants or allergens.\n- Keep your hands clean and moisturized.\n- Use gloves when handling chemicals or irritants.\n- Manage stress, as it can trigger or worsen certain conditions.\n\nA healthcare provider can diagnose the cause based on your symptoms and recommend appropriate treatment.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
